Like most schools, Excelsior Union High School has clearly defined groups - the haves' and the have nots'. When Jay Jay(Michael J. Fox) , class clown & champion of the nerds falls for the girlfriend of the town(Nancy McKeon) aristocrat Beau Middleton(Anthony Edwards), Beau & his friends set out to ruin Jay Jay's reputation....

This comedy/drama flick takes me back to memory lane to when I was 11 years old in the 5th grade when it debuted for the very first time on NBC in the Fall of 1983.

I found out in another review that Poison IVY is the one I was looking for, if Amazon had another one to send out to me of this movie, I would have taken it instead of refund.  But luckily I got a refund, because the movie I actually remember with nancy mkeon and Michael j. Fox is Poison Ivy and it is not available and is better than high School uSA, Save your money...

This movie brought back memories of my childhood.  NBC dominated made for tv movies during that decade.  This movie contained so many popular stars from the 60's, 70's, and 80's.  I highly suggest buying this if you're into the family friendly movie that always let's the good guys win.

I remember when HIGH SCHOOL U.S.A. first aired back in 1983.  It was a big deal at the time to have a made for TV family movie (do they even do that kind of thing anymore?) that featured the young actors of that period starring alongside the young actors of yesteryear (or now, the year before yesteryear).  Jo, Kimberly Drummond, Willis Jackson, and Alex P. Keaton were the students and Gilligan, Dobie Gillis, Eddie Haskell, and Wally Cleaver were among the teachers/faculty/parents.  It was creatively written, though many of the gags were lame and corny even for back then.

I won't say it's not corny.  I won't say it's not embarrassingly lame in some parts.  I won't say it's not too silly for it's own good.  But I also won't say it's not fun.  Indeed, for all it's lameness and corniness, this is still a fun movie to watch.

It's very disappointing that the only home versions of the made-for-TVer HIGH SCHOOL USA (1983) are questionable ones. The VHS manufacturer, UNITED AMERICAN VIDEO, dubbed their product at SLP speed, the very slowest, and without HiFi audio. The few tapes I own from them have a crap picture, a bad hiss in the sound and major tracking problems. As for the DVD outfit TRINITY HOME ENTERTAINMENT, their extensive catalog of skin flicks and slasher trash doesn't inspire me. After searching out reviews of their discs, I couldn't find anything specific to transfer quality, no raves or rants, yet I'm not prepared to plunge the necessary scratch to risk finding out if they are of better quality than UAE or not. Is it fair to judge a home video outfit by their catalog? That's an individual choice. I gave this one a pass, for what it's worth.

My older brother taped this off of TV years ago and it always became a running joke amongst myself and my siblings.  I was so excited to see it put onto DVD.  The movie itself is pure camp, but that it what makes it so enjoyable.  It is the epitome of 80's made-for-tv-movies with all the great stars of that time.  I highly recommend this for a laugh.

I had this movie on tape from tv probably close to 18 years ago...? Maybe that long...?  Anyway, I lost the tape of course and could never remember the name of this movie.  I was shocked to see this on Amazon for such a low price.  If you like 80's movies with pretty much every great 80's up & commers actors/actresses, buy this!!! I finally saw this movie. Fox starred in 3 high school movies from 1983-4. This one, Class of 1984 and of course Back to the Future. Try watching all 3 in a binge session if you can. High School is perhaps somewhat forgettable. But nice to see Bob Denver and Dawn Wells in their roles. And if you were around then, wonder where all those years wandered to.

It depicted some customs now discarded, like the roller skating rink. Ah darn! Great fun. And the fluffed out hair on those girls. Courtesy of Farah Fawcett. Something that would endure till the end of the 80s.
